habitat_description:
Restrictedly found in the Edwards Plateau in central Texas (Conant and Collins 1998). Range is from central to west Texas in the San Antonio to Big Bend area (Behler and King 1979).

Habitat includes limestone hill crevices and caves (Behler and King 1979). 
Considered common in rocky areas of central Texas in the Edwards Plateau west to the Stockton Plateau. Reproduction is terrestrial and very limited information is available on breeding microhabitat with few sightings of breeding that did not involve any nearby moisture. At other times, juvenile and adult habitat is characterized as rocky and densely vegetated as to provide moist protection. Found also talus slides, limestone bluffs and ledges, ravines and in nearby streams. Habitat also includes juniper-oak associations of the Balconian Province of Blair (Lannoo 2005).
